<subSubSection pageId="95" pageNumber="491" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="95.[115,1319,893,1508]" pageId="95" pageNumber="491">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[115,366,931,956]" pageId="95" pageNumber="491">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head—body 68-72 mm, tail 49-59 mm, hindfoot 12-12-5 mm. No specific data are available for body weight. Condylo-basal lengths are 17-6-18-2 mm. The Phu Quoc White-toothed Shrew is medium-sized. Tail is 69-87% of head-body length. Pelage is short and dense, dark gray dorsally and ventrally, with slight brownish hue. Tail is bicolored, dark gray dorsally, and slightly paler below. Bristle hairs are present on basal 60% oftail. Skull has broad and deep rostrum.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="95" pageNumber="491" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="95.[115,1319,893,1508]" pageId="95" pageNumber="491">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[115,227,1159,1192]" pageId="95" pageNumber="491">Habitat.</emphasis>
Only known from a dipterocarp forest, near fallen trees at bottom of a mountain, at elevations of 25-40 m.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
